A couple of glasses a week.

387
00:13:06,837 --> 00:13:07,298
In the week?

388
00:13:07,359 --> 00:13:07,558
Yeah.

389
00:13:07,600 --> 00:13:08,800
Not a lot at all really.

390
00:13:08,821 --> 00:13:09,081
OK.

391
00:13:09,101 --> 00:13:09,642
Good.

392
00:13:09,662 --> 00:13:10,302
And your diet?

393
00:13:10,322 --> 00:13:11,043
Do you eat well?

394
00:13:11,305 --> 00:13:11,544
Yeah.

395
00:13:11,565 --> 00:13:12,446
No, we eat really well.

396
00:13:13,067 --> 00:13:17,452
My girlfriend's, you know, really into healthy eating so we grow our own vegetables at home.

397
00:13:17,472 --> 00:13:18,254
Wonderful.

398
00:13:18,815 --> 00:13:19,375
Excellent.

399
00:13:19,475 --> 00:13:19,875
Great.

400
00:13:20,336 --> 00:13:21,859
And do you exercise?

401
00:13:21,838 --> 00:13:28,992
Not really, because I'm just on site so much, I'm busy all day, I'm very active during the day, but I don't really exercise outside.

402
00:13:29,092 --> 00:13:29,374
Right.

403
00:13:29,834 --> 00:13:37,889
I suppose if you could find that time, it would be relaxing, I suppose, to help, you know, good for your diabetes as well, if we could.

404
00:13:37,870 --> 00:13:40,533
I just want to sum up, Paul, if you don't mind.

405
00:13:41,274 --> 00:13:43,697
Please correct me if I've got any of it wrong.

406
00:13:44,158 --> 00:13:47,504
You've had this cough and sore throat for the last 3 days.

407
00:13:47,543 --> 00:13:52,651
Nothing makes it really better, or you have taken your paracetamol.

408
00:13:52,671 --> 00:13:54,072
That's helped a little bit.

409
00:13:54,553 --> 00:14:00,822
You've not had any blood in that phlegm, no fever, no unexplained weight loss.

410
00:14:00,802 --> 00:14:03,267
Breathing's okay as well.

411
00:14:03,867 --> 00:14:10,717
You've got type 2 diabetes because you take tablets for that and it's well controlled and so is your blood pressure.

412
00:14:11,359 --> 00:14:14,484
Your dad died sadly of a stroke.

413
00:14:15,826 --> 00:14:20,172
You live with your girlfriend and you're quite happy.

414
00:14:20,192 --> 00:14:26,642
Work is good and you just really want us to sort out your sore throat and cough.

415
00:14:26,622 --> 00:14:27,884
Yes, please.

416
00:14:27,943 --> 00:14:28,806
Okay, okay.

417
00:14:28,846 --> 00:14:32,052
Is there anything else you want to add to that before we move on?

418
00:14:32,933 --> 00:14:33,654
No, no, that's it I think.

419
00:14:33,956 --> 00:14:35,117
Alright, okay.

420
00:14:35,137 --> 00:14:45,316
Well, what we need to do now is to check some vital signs and I need to examine you before we could decide, you know, what's going on with your sore throat and cough and take it from there.

421
00:14:45,437 --> 00:14:46,398
Is that okay with you?

422
00:14:47,586 --> 00:14:47,661
fine.

423
00:14:47,681 --> 00:14:48,446
Good, thank you.

424
00:14:50,529 --> 00:14:53,894
Well that concludes our demonstration of the history taking process.

425
00:14:54,395 --> 00:15:00,560
Paul is a senior lecturer at the University and has kindly offered to give feedback from a patient perspective.

426
00:15:01,362 --> 00:15:11,331
The key principles used in the history taking process was first and foremost me as the practitioner ensuring that the environment was safe and accessible for the patient.

427
00:15:11,951 --> 00:15:18,973
I was also mindful to avoid interruptions thus maintaining the patient's privacy and confidentiality.

428
00:15:19,841 --> 00:15:26,250
As I called a patient in I was mindful not to use the patient's first name but to seek permission.

429
00:15:26,892 --> 00:15:29,355
So how did you feel about that Paul?

430
00:15:29,375 --> 00:15:40,757
I thought that was quite appropriate and I felt that you respected my right to be called Mr Collins or Paul accordingly and I was happy to be called Paul.

431
00:15:40,737 --> 00:15:41,718
Great.

432
00:15:41,738 --> 00:15:51,910
I also felt it was imperative that I gained informed consent and so I told the patient at the outset what was to be expected and seeked consent from him.

433
00:15:52,750 --> 00:16:01,740
I also thought that it was important that I used an open-ended question at the outset so that the patient could tell his story in his own words.

434
00:16:02,280 --> 00:16:03,623
How did you find that?

435
00:16:03,603 --> 00:16:10,413
I thought that was good and I certainly had the opportunity to talk about what was concerning me which was obviously the cough.

436
00:16:12,255 --> 00:16:14,519
So yeah, I got that out of the way quite quickly I think.

437
00:16:14,799 --> 00:16:15,641
Great, all good.

438
00:16:16,021 --> 00:16:26,277
The other thing is although I'm wanting the patient to tell their own story, I also am mindful of the red flags, thus ruling out life-threatening causes.

439
00:16:26,918 --> 00:16:32,866
I tried to be systematic but I also wanted to respond to the patient's cues as well.

440
00:16:32,846 --> 00:16:42,038
And so whenever the patient gave a leading answer, I would allow him the scope to explore that further.

441
00:16:43,139 --> 00:16:53,791
I then went through the key processes of history taking and then allowed at the very end to sum up, thus allowing the patient to clarify from their perspective.

442
00:16:53,771 --> 00:17:05,826
I was mindful as well not to use jargons but how did you feel because sometimes we get lost as practitioners and we see medical jargons as normal terminology.

443
00:17:05,846 --> 00:17:19,422
I think on the whole it was very good and for the most part it was fairly free of medical jargon although I know at 1 point you did ask about social history which I think had the potential to confuse somebody

444
00:17:20,354 --> 00:17:23,432
Of course, I didn't think of it like that, but that's so right.

445
00:17:24,012 --> 00:17:25,778
Absolutely.

446
00:17:25,837 --> 00:17:31,373
I mean, the questions, once you'd said you were going to ask about the social history, I think the questions were absolutely fine.

447
00:17:31,413 --> 00:17:36,807
It's just that headlining really of that particular area of history taking, perhaps.

448
00:17:36,787 --> 00:17:40,094
and that's important for me to note as a practitioner.

449
00:17:40,853 --> 00:17:50,750
Well, that concludes the key steps in history taking process and we hope that we've helped you to add structure and depth to your history taking in the clinical setting.

450
00:17:52,270 --> 00:18:00,766
And I will put some referencing online for you that will help you to explore further the key issues surrounding history taking.

451
00:18:01,305 --> 00:18:02,077
Thank you very much.

